excerpt: 20th-century church featuring imposing, Byzantine-inspired architecture & a soaring central dome.
detail_description: Nestled in the vibrant Vracar district of Belgrade, the Temple of Saint Sava stands as a monumental testament to Byzantine-inspired architecture. This 20th-century marvel is not only one of the largest Orthodox churches globally but also features an awe-inspiring central dome that dominates the skyline, making it a must-see for any traveler. Its grandeur and intricate design draw visitors from all corners, eager to experience its spiritual ambiance and historical significance.
name: Church of Saint Sava

excerpt: Exhibits of the personal effects, instruments & drawings of electrical engineer Nikola Tesla.
detail_description: The Nikola Tesla Museum in Belgrade is a tribute to the life and work of the renowned electrical engineer, Nikola Tesla. Housed in a charming residential villa, it showcases his personal effects, instruments, and original drawings that revolutionized energy production and distribution. The museum offers both memorial exhibits and interactive displays featuring 3D computer-generated models of Tesla's inventions.
name: Nikola Tesla Museum

excerpt: Leisure destination on a river peninsula featuring many sports facilities, plus dining & shopping.
detail_description: Nestled on a picturesque river peninsula, Ada Ciganlija is the ultimate leisure destination in Belgrade, especially during the summer months. This stunning locale boasts a 4.2 km long artificial lake that serves as a playground for both kids and adults. Here, you can indulge in various activities such as sailing, swimming, and waterskiing or simply bask in the sun on its sandy beaches.
name: Ada Ciganlija

excerpt: Skadarlija is a vintage street, an urban neighborhood and former municipality of Belgrade, Serbia, located in the Belgrade municipality of Stari Grad. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Skadarlija, often referred to as the bohemian quarter of Belgrade, is a charming vintage street that captures the essence of artistic life in Serbia. Nestled within the Stari Grad municipality, this vibrant neighborhood is just a short stroll from Republic Square. Once home to artists associated with the National Theatre in the 19th century, Skadarlija has transformed into a lively hub known for its traditional kafanas—Serbian restaurants where live music fills the air both day and night.
name: Skadarlija

excerpt: Busy central square & public-transport hub with an iconic equestrian statue of Prince Michael.
detail_description: Republic Square is a bustling central square and transportation hub in Belgrade's old town, featuring the iconic equestrian statue of Prince Michael. It is conveniently located near Knez Mihailova Street, offering easy access to dining and shopping options. The area is known for its vibrant nightlife, with nearby restaurants like Impression Lanzhou and Panda Tianfu. Additionally, the square is home to prestigious cultural institutions such as the National Museum and National Theatre.
name: Republic Square

excerpt: Expansive park featuring a historic fortress with a museum, a zoo, walking paths & river views.
detail_description: Kalemegdan is a sprawling park that houses a historic fortress, complete with a museum and zoo. The park offers scenic walking paths and stunning views of the nearby rivers. Adjacent to the park, visitors can explore a charming street lined with ice cream shops, coffee houses, bakeries, and various retail spaces offering handcrafted and vintage items. Belgrade's top attraction, Kalemegdan Park or Belgrade Fortress, provides panoramic views of the city and its surroundings.
name: Kalemegdan

excerpt: This ancient fortress sits atop a clifflike ridge overlooking the river & offers lush park areas.
detail_description: Nestled atop a dramatic ridge, the Belgrade Fortress, also known as Kalemegdan Park, is an essential starting point for any exploration of this vibrant city. This historic site not only boasts stunning views over the confluence of two rivers but also serves as a sprawling park filled with lush greenery. The fortress itself is divided into Upper and Lower City sections, each brimming with attractions like the iconic Victor Monument, Military Museum, Nebojsa Tower, and Saint Petka's Church.
name: Belgrade Fortress

excerpt: Bohemian, villagelike Zemun is known for its cafes, lively late-night bars, and the fish restaurants along its riverside promenade. Gardoš hill, topped by an 1896 tower, offers Danube and city views. Ornate churches include baroque St. Nicholas, with murals and glittering icons. The Madlenianum presents opera and theater, and the Zemun Home Museum has local history exhibits in an elegant 19th-century building.
detail_description: Zemun, a bohemian and picturesque town in the southwestern corner of Serbia, is a charming destination known for its cozy cafes, vibrant late-night bars, and delightful fish restaurants along the riverside promenade. The iconic Gardoš hill boasts a historic tower offering breathtaking views of the Danube and the city. Visitors can explore ornate churches like the baroque St. Nicholas adorned with murals and glittering icons.
name: Zemun

excerpt: Large museum with a celebrated European art collection, ancient artifacts & historical objects.
detail_description: The National Museum of Serbia is a large museum featuring a renowned European art collection, ancient artifacts, and historical objects. The building's Bauhaus-style facade sets the stage for an impressive interior just a short walk from popular tourist spots like Knez Mihailova and the Theater. Meanwhile, the Yugoslav History Museum showcases Tito's personal belongings, cultural artifacts, and temporary exhibitions in a post-war era building.
name: National Museum of Serbia

excerpt: Tall reconstructed tower featuring an observation deck, restaurant, souvenir shop & ethno-gallery.
detail_description: Avala Tower is a reconstructed landmark TV tower that was destroyed during the 1999 NATO bombing of Serbia and later rebuilt in 2010. It features an observation deck, restaurant, souvenir shop, ethno-gallery, sports fields, and outdoor gym. Visitors can admire the panoramic view of the Serbian landscape around Avala hill and enjoy the adrenaline rush at the top of the tower.
name: Avala Tower

excerpt: Serbian Orthodox church at Kalemegdan Fortress, once used to store gunpowder & as a military church.
detail_description: Nestled within the historic Kalemegdan Fortress, Ružica Church stands as a testament to Belgrade's rich heritage. This Serbian Orthodox church, dedicated to Saint Mary, is not only the oldest in the city but also one of Serbia's most significant religious sites. Its origins trace back to the 13th century, with its first documented mention appearing in the 1400s.
name: Ružica Church

excerpt: Military museum housed in a former fortress, displaying ancient & modern artifacts & weaponry.
detail_description: Nestled within a historic fortress, the Military Museum in Belgrade offers an intriguing glimpse into the military heritage of Serbia. This captivating museum showcases a diverse collection of artifacts and weaponry that spans both ancient and modern times. Visitors can immerse themselves in the rich tapestry of military history, exploring exhibits featuring tanks, cannons, and various combat equipment like shields, spears, swords, and daggers. The museum serves as a reminder of how past military endeavors have shaped nations today.
name: Military Museum

excerpt: Landmark burial site of Josip Broz Tito, former Yugoslavian President, with a garden & terrace.
detail_description: House of Flowers, the burial site of Josip Broz Tito, offers a unique insight into the Communist era in Serbia. The Museum of Yugoslavia provides a nuanced understanding of this period and its significance. While modern Belgrade is filled with entertainment, a historical tour to this landmark is essential to grasp life during Yugoslavia's reign. The museum preserves the view of Serbia from that time and serves as an important pilgrimage site for those seeking to understand the region's history.
name: House of Flowers

excerpt: History museum on Yugoslavia & its former President Josip Broz Tito, who is buried on the grounds.
detail_description: The Museum of Yugoslavia in Belgrade is a unique institution that aims to foster an understanding of the past and its relevance to the present. It serves as a platform for open dialogue, knowledge exchange, and exploration of social and cultural phenomena from the 20th century. The museum's focus spans from the creation of the Yugoslav state as a kingdom to its dissolution in the early 1990s.
name: Museum of Yugoslavia

excerpt: Striking, modern museum with a vast collection of contemporary paintings, sculpture & visual arts.
detail_description: The Museum of Contemporary Art is a modern and impressive museum housing a vast collection of contemporary paintings, sculpture, and visual arts. It was founded in 1965 with the aim of showcasing prominent artists and movements in Yugoslav, Serbian, and international 20th-century art. The museum's main collection includes over 8000 artworks created in the Yugoslav region between 1900 and 1991.
name: Museum of contemporary art

excerpt: Belgrade is the capital of the southeast European country of Serbia. Its most significant landmark is the Beogradska Tvrđava, an imposing fortress at the confluence of the Danube and the Sava rivers. The fort is a testament to the city’s strategic importance to the Roman, Byzantine, Ottoman, Serbian and Austrian empires, and it's now the site of several museums as well as Kalemegdan, a vast park.
detail_description: Belgrade, the capital of Serbia, boasts the impressive Beogradska Tvrđava fortress at the confluence of the Danube and Sava rivers. This historic site has witnessed various empires and now houses museums and Kalemegdan park. Additionally, visitors can enjoy Sakura, an exclusive Far Eastern restaurant with stunning views. Sokobanja, a popular spa town near Belgrade, has attracted famous figures like Branislav Nusic and Nobel laureate Ivo Andric.
name: Belgrade

excerpt: Botanical park featuring an arboretum with a Japanese garden & a greenhouse for tropical plants.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Belgrade, Botanical Garden "Jevremovac" is a captivating oasis boasting lush vegetation, a serene Japanese garden, and an enchanting old greenhouse. Spanning approximately 5 hectares, this historic garden is home to over 350 tree and bush species from around the world. Initially established in the 19th century at the behest of Josif Pancic, it exudes cultural and architectural significance as one of the oldest botanical gardens globally.
name: Jevremovac Botanical Garden

excerpt: Park with 19th-century origins & a landmark plane tree, popular for picnics, hikes & carriage rides.
detail_description: Topčider Park, the first public park in Belgrade and Serbia, is a stunning oasis that dates back to the 19th century. Nestled away from the city's hustle and bustle, this picturesque park is perfect for leisurely picnics, serene hikes, or charming carriage rides. With its vast green spaces and majestic leafy trees, Topčider offers visitors a chance to unwind amidst nature's beauty.
name: Topčider park

excerpt: Green space with shade trees, paved jogging paths, a playground & large sports complex.
detail_description: Tasmajdan is a vibrant park located in the downtown area, offering a mix of historical and modern attractions. It features paved jogging paths, shaded areas with trees, and a large sports complex. The park is surrounded by must-see landmarks such as St. Mark's Church, the country's Parliament, and the main Post Office building. Tasmajdan has an interesting history and is situated above famous city caves.
name: Tasmajdan | Sportsko rekreativni centar | Park

excerpt: Grand Serbian Orthodox church completed in 1940, featuring a crypt & several notable icons.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Belgrade, St. Mark Orthodox Church stands as a magnificent testament to Serbian heritage and spirituality. Completed in 1940, this grand structure showcases stunning Serbo-Byzantine architecture crafted by the Krstic brothers, replacing an earlier church from 1835. Located within Tasmajdan Park and close to Serbia's Parliament, it is not only one of the largest churches in the country but also a significant cultural landmark.
name: St. Mark Orthodox Church

excerpt: Built in the 1600s during the Ottoman Empire, this stone mosque features a octagonal dome & minaret.
detail_description: Bajrakli Mosque, the only mosque in Belgrade, dates back to the 1600s when it was built during the Ottoman Empire. It features an octagonal dome and a minaret. The mosque has a rich history as it was converted into a Catholic church during the Austro-Hungarian occupation but later restored to its original purpose when the Ottomans regained control of Serbia.
name: Bajrakli Mosque

excerpt: Intimate city zoo (7 hectares) that houses a variety of birds, plus wolves, white lions & tigers.
detail_description: Belgrade Zoo, located on the Danube River, is a charming wildlife park that spans 7 hectares and houses around 800 animals from 210 different species. It's a great place to visit with children, offering thrilling experiences such as observing birds, predatory animals, and wild creatures. The zoo is part of the Belgrade Fortress/Kalemegdan Park area and is known for its variety of birds as well as its wolves, white lions, and tigers.
name: Belgrade Zoo
address: Mali Kalemegdan 8, Belgrade 11000, Serbia Belgrade RS, 11000, Serbia

excerpt: A 1,677-foot mountain & historic mining site covered in lush forest with city views.
detail_description: Avala is a 1,677-foot mountain located just ten kilometers from Belgrade. It has been a significant site for various civilizations throughout history and is now a protected natural area in Serbia. The lush forest on the mountain is home to eight sources of pure mountain water, making it an ideal spot for day trips and picnics. Visitors can enjoy stunning views of Belgrade from the top of the mountain and engage in activities such as leisurely walks, cycling, and hiking.
name: Avala

excerpt: Zemunski Kej is an urban neighborhood of Belgrade, the capital of Serbia. It is located in Belgrade's municipality of Zemun. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Zemunski Kej is a vibrant urban area situated in Belgrade, Serbia. This neighborhood, located within the municipality of Zemun, is renowned for its charming riverside promenade adorned with cozy cafes, lively bars, and delightful fish restaurants. Notably, Cafeteria Gardos and Tia Gelateria are popular spots to enjoy a leisurely drink or treat before embarking on a scenic walk up the hill to Gardos Tower.
name: Zemunski Kej

excerpt: Savamala is an urban neighborhood of Belgrade, the capital of Serbia. It is located in Belgrade's municipalities of Savski Venac and Stari Grad. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Savamala, situated in the heart of Belgrade, Serbia, is an urban neighborhood that spans across the municipalities of Savski Venac and Stari Grad. This vibrant area offers a mix of cultural attractions, trendy bars, and artistic spaces. With its central location, Savamala is a hub for creativity and urban exploration in the capital city.
name: Savamala

detail_description: Belgrade Waterfront is a recently developed riverside area featuring a charming promenade lined with an array of dining options, cafes, and retail stores. One notable highlight is Beton Hala, a former concrete hall that has been transformed into a collection of stylish restaurants. Among the popular choices is Comunale, an elegant Italian eatery offering modern cuisine. This vibrant destination offers visitors the opportunity to enjoy leisurely strolls along the river while indulging in diverse culinary experiences and shopping opportunities.
name: Belgrade Waterfront

detail_description: When you think of Belgrade, the splavovi, or rafts, are an essential part of its allure. These floating venues transform the Sava and Danube rivers into lively hubs for nightlife enthusiasts. The experience is truly one-of-a-kind; it’s not just about partying on a raft but enjoying beautifully crafted houses that float on water. With top-notch craftsmanship evident in their construction, these rafts are built by skilled artisans who take pride in their work.
name: SPLAVOVI „POPOVIĆ"

excerpt: Domed & porticoed parliament building with monthly public tours of inner halls, statues & frescoes.
detail_description: The House of the National Assembly of the Republic of Serbia is a stunning Beaux-Arts structure that stands as a testament to the country's rich history and architectural beauty. Nestled in Belgrade, this impressive building was constructed on the site of the former Batal Mosque after Serbia's independence in 1878. Its construction faced numerous delays due to historical events like wars and economic challenges, but it ultimately emerged as a symbol of national pride.
name: House of the National Assembly of the Republic of Serbia

excerpt: Home to rare plants & mammals, this river island serves as the nesting ground for many bird species.
detail_description: Great War Island is a captivating destination that beautifully blends nature and history. This river island is not only a sanctuary for rare plants and mammals but also serves as a vital nesting ground for various bird species, making it an ecological treasure. A recent kayaking tour on the island allowed participants of all skill levels to explore its stunning scenery while enjoying the unique perspective of Belgrade from the water.
name: Great War Island

detail_description: The National Theatre in Belgrade, located on Republic Square, is a historic venue that has been showcasing Serbian culture since 1869. Despite war damage and architectural updates, it remains a revered symbol of the country's artistic heritage. Visitors can take backstage tours during the day to witness wardrobe and scenery maintenance and enjoy performances by resident singers. The square itself is a popular meeting point with landmarks like the National Museum and Prince Mihailo monument. It also hosts various events including concerts and protests.
name: National Theatre in Belgrade

excerpt:
Dorćol is an affluent urban neighborhood of Belgrade, the capital of Serbia. It is located in Belgrade's municipality of Stari Grad.
Located along the right bank of the Danube, Dorćol is the oldest surviving neighborhood in Belgrade. It is known for its specific urban charm and the mentality of its residents. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Dorćol, an upscale urban area in Belgrade, Serbia, is situated on the right bank of the Danube and falls under the municipality of Stari Grad. As the oldest surviving neighborhood in Belgrade, it exudes a distinctive urban charm and is renowned for its residents' mentality. The neighborhood boasts numerous cafes like Meduza for a morning caffeine fix before venturing across the river to explore Zemun's independent municipality.
name: Dorćol

excerpt: Gardoš is an urban neighborhood of Belgrade, the capital of Serbia. It is located in Belgrade's municipality of Zemun. Located on the slopes of the hill of the same name, with its tower and preserved old architecture, Gardoš is the major historical landmark of Zemun. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Gardoš, situated in the Zemun municipality of Belgrade, Serbia, is a charming urban neighborhood known for its historical significance. Perched on the slopes of Gardoš hill, it boasts a prominent tower and well-preserved old architecture, making it a major landmark in Zemun. Visitors can leisurely explore Gardoš and then take a relaxed stroll to New Belgrade to witness Tito's vision of a modern capital city.
name: Gardoš

excerpt: National museum presenting Serbian archaeology, history & ethnography exhibits in an airy space.
detail_description: The Historical Museum of Serbia, located on Nikola Pašić Square, offers a comprehensive presentation of Serbian archaeology, history, and ethnography. The museum primarily hosts temporary exhibitions that cover various themes from Serbia's past. Recent exhibits have delved into topics such as the 13th-century prince and monk St.
name: Historical Museum of Serbia

excerpt: Historic royal palace with a spacious,18th century–style interior & large Venetian chandeliers.
detail_description: The White Palace, located in the upscale Dedinje neighborhood south of the city, is a historic royal palace with an 18th-century style interior and grand Venetian chandeliers. Built by King Alexander in the 1930s for his three sons, this Neo-Palladian palace boasts heavy French influence and stands on the same grounds as the nearby Royal Palace. While not open for casual visits, tours are available during summer months by booking in advance through the tourist board.
name: The White Palace
address: The Royal Palace, Bulevar kneza Aleksandra Karađorđevića 96, Beograd 11040, Serbia

detail_description: Nikola Pašić Square, the newest square in Belgrade, is surrounded by significant government buildings such as the National Assembly of the Republic of Serbia, constructed at the beginning of the 20th century. The square also features the Old Palace, once home to King Milan Obrenovic and now serving as the Mayor's office, and the New Palace, former residence of Karadjordjevic Royal Family and current office of the President.
name: Nikola Pašić Square

excerpt: Zeleni Venac or colloquially Zelenjak is an urban neighborhood of Belgrade, the capital of Serbia. It is located in the Belgrade's municipalities of Savski Venac and Stari Grad. Wikipedia.
name: Zeleni Venac

excerpt: Museum dedicated to Serbian culture & ethnography, with jewelry, clothes, weapons & other artifacts.
detail_description: The Ethnographic Museum in Belgrade, Serbia, is a treasure trove of artifacts and exhibits dedicated to Serbian culture and ethnography. Established in 1901, it stands as one of the oldest museum buildings in the region. With a vast collection of over 150,000 items including jewelry, clothing, weapons, folk costumes, trade devices, crafts, furniture and dishes from different historical periods such as ancient history and the Middle Ages.
name: Ethnographic Museum

detail_description: Nebojša Tower, also known as Kula Nebojša or Nebojsina Kula, stands within Belgrade Fortress as a testament to the city's history. Originally constructed in 1460 by the Hungarians to protect the area, it later served as a grim dungeon for prisoners. The tower's name, "Nebojša," translates to "fearless" in Serbian and reflects its resilient nature.
name: Nebojša Tower

detail_description: Bajloni Market, also known as Skadarlija Market, is a beloved open-air market located in the heart of Belgrade. This vibrant marketplace hosts popular monthly events featuring live music and a variety of stalls offering delicacies, homeware, wine, and art. The market's picturesque setting at the bottom of Skadarska Street adds to its charm and makes it a favorite among locals and visitors alike.
name: Bajloni Market Belgrade

excerpt: Family-oriented visitor center with games & puzzles based around optical effects & illusions.
detail_description: The Museum of Illusions is a museum filled with optical effects and illusions that will challenge your sense of reality. It is perfect for children, but also a great place for adults to visit. There are many photo opportunities here that are sure to make memories for a lifetime.
name: Museum of Illusions

excerpt: Roomy, covered venue with stalls selling fruits, vegetables, meat & other regional products.
detail_description: Zeleni Venac, also known as Green Wreath, is a bustling and spacious covered market in Belgrade. Despite its name, it's not particularly lush due to its location near a busy public transport hub. However, it offers an authentic experience of the city and is a great place to interact with locals while sampling fresh produce. The market has a rich history dating back 170 years and is one of the oldest still operating today.
name: Farmer's market "Zeleni venac"

excerpt: Stately former royal palace of the Obrenović dynasty, featuring balconies, Doric columns & gardens.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Belgrade, The Old Palace stands as a magnificent testament to Serbia's royal history. Constructed between 1882 and 1884, this architectural gem was originally home to the Obrenović dynasty before later serving the Karadjordjević family. With its stunning Doric columns and elegant balconies, it exudes a stately charm that captivates visitors.
name: The Old Palace

detail_description: DRUM - Belgrade underground society is a popular spot among locals and tourists alike. The club boasts great DJs, an energetic atmosphere with youth dancing, and a prime location in the heart of Belgrade. It's known for its excellent sound system and old-school club vibe, making it a favorite among those looking for a memorable night out. The staff are also praised for their friendliness and service, adding to the overall positive experience at DRUM.
name: DRUM - Belgrade underground society

detail_description: Novi Dvor, or New Palace, is a significant landmark in central Belgrade. It was once the royal residence for the Karadordevic dynasty and played a role in the history of Serbia and Yugoslavia. Situated across from Stari Dvor (Old Palace), both structures are part of a grand ensemble on Kralja Milana. The Old Palace boasts Beaux-Arts architecture and interiors imported from Vienna.
name: Novi Dvor

detail_description: The Roman Well, located near the Pobednik and Kings Gate in Belgrade, is a historical site within the Belgrade Fortress. Despite its name, it was actually built by Austrians in the 18th century as part of their claim to inheritance over the Roman Empire. Originally known as the Big Well, it was later renamed as the Roman Well.
name: Roman well

detail_description: Nestled on the lively Knez Mihailova Street, Mama Shelter Belgrade boasts a vibrant rooftop terrace with a mix of seating options, a ping-pong table, and stunning panoramic views of the Belgrade skyline. The rooftop bar serves an array of frozen cocktails, signature drinks, refreshing juices, and premium spirits alongside Serbian dishes, pan-Mediterranean cuisine, and wood-fired oven pizzas.
name: Mama Shelter Belgrade

detail_description: Crkva Svetog Marka, also known as the Church of Saint Mark, is a significant landmark in Belgrade with a rich history dating back several centuries. The modern version of the church was completed in 1940 and showcases beautiful Serbo-Byzantine architectural influences. It was once the largest church in Belgrade and continues to be an important Orthodox sanctuary.
name: Crkva Svetog Marka

detail_description: Hotel Jugoslavija, a historic establishment in Belgrade, suffered damage during the 1999 NATO bombing but has since been restored and reopened. It stands as a massive monument of the former republic of Yugoslavia. Situated near the first basic court and close to various amenities, it offers convenience for travelers. The hotel is one of the oldest in town and holds significance from the Yugoslav era.
name: Hotel Jugoslavija

detail_description: Belgrade Fortress, located in the heart of the city at Republic Square, is a must-visit destination. The fortress offers stunning views of the Danube and Sava rivers from Kalemegdan Park. As you explore this historic site, you'll also encounter the charming Bohemian quarter and Republic Square. It's a perfect starting point for immersing yourself in Belgrade's rich history and vibrant culture.
name: Belgrade fortress
